18:00.400 --> 18:05.680
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

18:08.320 --> 18:09.980
And here are your hosts.

18:13.940 --> 18:14.820
This is David B.

18:16.240 --> 18:22.460
Horror and fantasy are two movie categories that are closely related to science fiction, and they've both been very popular in the last year or so.

18:22.880 --> 18:27.320
And the popularity of both of them, as with science fiction, reflects something found in our present society.

18:27.740 --> 18:32.720
We spoke recently with Roger Ebert, film critic and science fiction fan, about the popularity of the field.

18:33.280 --> 18:39.740
We asked him if the Science Fiction Movie Boom reflects our concern with the space program and our desire to get off the earth before we ruin or destroy it.

18:40.680 --> 18:53.340
No, I don't think so. I think maybe some of the fascination with 2001 might have been because it came out at a time when amazing things were happening in space and we were getting ready to land on the moon and so forth.

18:54.100 --> 19:08.600
But I believe that the space movies today, like Star Wars and The Empire Strikes Back, are identified with primarily in the same way that Rage of the Lost Ark is, as a pick-a-resk adventure.

19:09.740 --> 19:18.620
And when we talk about science fiction, I gather that you and I both kind of tacitly did not include horror films.

19:19.460 --> 19:23.980
I think a psychiatrist might say something like this, or at least I've heard this theory.

19:24.860 --> 19:34.940
It's not so much that the space films indicate our feeling that there's a new frontier to be conquered, as that the monster films indicate our fear of technology.

19:34.940 --> 19:47.200
And there is an old theory that at any time when mankind, in recent years, in the 20th century, when people, when the public has started to feel threatened by the bomb or by technology,

19:47.480 --> 19:53.920
then you get a lot of horror pictures because the message seems to be science will get out of control. Science will kill us.

19:53.920 --> 19:59.100
There'll be some kind of a virus or giant grasshoppers or something will happen.

19:59.780 --> 20:05.920
And scanners or other terrible things will be unleashed upon the population.

20:06.900 --> 20:09.760
Ebert dislikes one particular aspect of current horror movies.

20:10.560 --> 20:15.040
I'll tell you one thing that's happening. I'm getting awfully bored by special effects makeup.

20:16.160 --> 20:26.180
It's only been about 18 months since the big breakthroughs of American werewolf in London and so forth.

20:27.300 --> 20:34.640
And already you get the close up of the face and the jaw begins to pulsate and then the face begins to expand and there's a face inside trying to get out.

20:35.180 --> 20:40.340
I've seen it now. I've seen it so many times that it's boring. I want to get out with a story.

20:45.480 --> 20:54.440
The World of the Dead

20:55.920 --> 21:05.080
Fantasy, as distinguished from science fiction, is also currently popular with movies like The Sword and the Sorcerer, Beastsmaster, The Cat People and Dragonslayer.

21:05.480 --> 21:08.800
We asked Ebert if the quality of fantasy could equal that of current science fiction.

21:09.460 --> 21:16.800
Well, the problem with fantasy is that science fiction is allegedly plausible.

21:17.880 --> 21:22.540
Although we could have a lot of questions about how much, for example, of Star Wars is really plausible.

21:24.100 --> 21:37.180
Fantasy is not supposed to be plausible, but the problem is most fantasy movies seem to be limited to sword and sorcery types of Conan the Barbarian,

21:38.360 --> 21:40.960
the Sword and the Sorcerer, and movies like that.

21:41.580 --> 21:44.020
Or you get an animated film like Lord of the Rings.

21:44.740 --> 21:53.180
I have not seen very much of the kind of fantasy, for example, the fantasy and science fiction magazine helped to popularize.

21:54.520 --> 22:03.000
Fantasy in that it has to do with the whimsy of magic or impossible things intruding into real life.

22:04.100 --> 22:10.020
Those kinds of movies are hard to do and it takes a lot of nerve to do them.

22:10.060 --> 22:18.780
It's one thing to have some broad falling out of her leopard skin bikini and some big brood with a sword and the rippling pectorals and so forth.

22:19.320 --> 22:23.780
But it's another thing to have the imagination to really create a fantasy.

