23:31.220 --> 23:35.240
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:50.320 --> 23:55.620
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

23:58.300 --> 23:59.940
And here are your hosts.

24:04.300 --> 24:06.780
This is Bill Vernon and David Cruz.

24:07.080 --> 24:09.880
In the late 1930s, science fiction was in transition.

24:10.560 --> 24:15.400
In one sense it was becoming more sophisticated, outgrowing its early emphasis on space opera.

24:15.880 --> 24:19.020
Jack Williamson, who wrote Space Opera, considers this change natural.

24:19.920 --> 24:24.440
I was growing up and the readers were growing up.

24:24.860 --> 24:30.600
That's something that's been going on in science fiction, at least in American science fiction all along.

24:30.720 --> 24:38.420
I think you can draw a distinction between, let's say, European or mainstream science fiction on the one hand,

24:38.540 --> 24:46.840
which has always been recognized and treated as literature and part of American science fiction,

24:46.840 --> 24:48.820
which was looked down on.

24:49.240 --> 24:56.660
But as the readers of that grew older, some of them started writing, some of them started editing magazines,

24:56.960 --> 25:10.380
most of them outgrew science fiction, but some of them didn't, so there was a continual increase in the education, the sophistication, and so forth, the whole field.

25:11.160 --> 25:18.640
Among these readers of pulp science fiction were a few who developed into those authors whose work defined what science fiction would become in later years.

25:19.200 --> 25:27.520
These early readers were people like Isaac Asimov, Robert Heinlein, A. E. Van Vogt, Theodore Sturgeon, L. Sprague de Kamp, Frederick Poel, and Hal Clement.

25:28.200 --> 25:34.920
And these authors are now the classics, those who wrote in that very special period of science fiction called the Golden Age.

25:35.800 --> 25:43.320
A. E. Van Vogt, looking back at that period, says that he read the authors who were starting out then with him, but that he had no idea they were doing anything special.

26:05.040 --> 26:11.800
You know, I mean, we were just doing our thing, and everybody was evidently stimulated in a special way.

26:12.260 --> 26:16.520
Frederick Poel belonged to a group of writers and fans in New York called the Futurians.

26:17.060 --> 26:20.560
He remembers the closeness of the group and how they would help each other.

26:21.480 --> 26:28.980
Well, science fiction has some special traits, and one of them is that its readers herd together as much as they can.

26:28.980 --> 26:34.260
They form fan clubs and associations and correspond to groups and so on.

26:34.960 --> 26:46.240
And in New York City, there were quite a few science fiction fans, and about 25 or 30 most of whom wanted to be writers formed a club called the Futurians.

26:47.000 --> 26:53.560
There are people like Cyril Karnblast, Isaac Asimov, Damon Knight, and myself, quite a few others.

26:53.560 --> 27:02.640
We did discuss each other's work a lot, and I guess in the process of criticizing it, there was a lot of help given.

27:03.260 --> 27:16.700
I think the biggest factor that made it easier for a lot of us to go on with writing was just the knowledge that other people were doing it, and also the fact that we collaborated a lot.

27:16.700 --> 27:32.660
We remedied each other's deficiencies by writing, I mean by collaborating on single stories, and although most of the stories were not very good, we did learn something by seeing how other people would tackle the same subjects we were writing about.

27:33.960 --> 27:43.320
Elsprague de Camp also remembers this closeness among writers at the beginning of the Golden Age, but like VanVote, de Camp says that the authors had no sense of participating in anything special.

27:44.060 --> 28:03.360
Well, I daresay that various ones of us did have their greens and fancies at times, and wondered how it was all going to come out, and would this become, would the genre expand and take over the mainstream and various things of that sort?

28:05.420 --> 28:10.440
But as to that mostly, as I said, it was simply a matter of making a living.

28:10.440 --> 28:15.640
But the living those young writers made is the foundation of today's science fiction.

28:22.900 --> 28:31.600
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

28:40.440 --> 29:02.580
Thank you for watching.

